import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_random_images(images, labels, class_label, class_name, n=4):
    indices = np.where(labels == class_label)[0]
    selected = np.random.choice(indices, n, replace=False)

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 3))
    for i, idx in enumerate(selected):
        plt.subplot(1, n, i+1)
        plt.imshow(images[idx])
        plt.title(class_name)
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Plot for each class
plot_random_images(images, labels['Label'].values, 1, "With Helmet")
plot_random_images(images, labels['Label'].values, 0, "Without Helmet")

def compare_preprocessing(rgb_images, gray_images, labels, n=4):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
    for i in range(n):
        idx = np.random.randint(0, len(rgb_images))

        # RGB image
        plt.subplot(2, n, i+1)
        plt.imshow(rgb_images[idx])
        plt.title(f"Original - {labels[idx]}")
        plt.axis('off')

        # Grayscale image
        plt.subplot(2, n, n+i+1)
        plt.imshow(gray_images[idx].reshape(200, 200), cmap='gray')
        plt.title(f"Grayscale - {labels[idx]}")
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

compare_preprocessing(images, images_gray, labels['Label'].values)

In [31]:
# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using statsmodels
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # checking which probabilities are greater than threshold
    pred = model.predict(predictors).reshape(-1)>0.5

    target = target.to_numpy().reshape(-1)


    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred, average='weighted')  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame({"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1 Score": f1,},index=[0],)

    return df_perf
In [33]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(model,predictors,target,ml=False):
    """
    Function to plot the confusion matrix

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    ml: To specify if the model used is an sklearn ML model or not (True means ML model)
    """

    # checking which probabilities are greater than threshold
    pred = model.predict(predictors).reshape(-1)>0.5

    target = target.to_numpy().reshape(-1)

    # Plotting the Confusion Matrix using confusion matrix() function which is also predefined tensorflow module
    confusion_matrix = tf.math.confusion_matrix(target,pred)
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
    sns.heatmap(
        confusion_matrix,
        annot=True,
        linewidths=.4,
        fmt="d",
        square=True,
        ax=ax
    )
    plt.show()

Import VGG-16 Base Model¶

In [ ]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Flatten, Dense, Dropout, Input
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

Define the Model¶

In [ ]:
# Convert grayscale (1-channel) to RGB (3-channel)
X_train_vgg = np.repeat(X_train, 3, axis=-1)
X_val_vgg = np.repeat(X_val, 3, axis=-1)

# Define base model (without top classifier layers)
vgg_base = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(200, 200, 3))

# Freeze the base layers
for layer in vgg_base.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

# Add custom classifier on top
x = vgg_base.output
x = Flatten()(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
predictions = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)

# Final model
vgg_model = Model(inputs=vgg_base.input, outputs=predictions)

Validation Accuracy: 1.0000

Observation¶

The VGG-16 model achieved a perfect validation accuracy of 100%, significantly outperforming the basic CNN. This result indicates that transfer learning using pre-trained weights from ImageNet allowed the model to generalize extremely well to our helmet detection task. However, such perfect accuracy might also hint at potential overfitting if the validation set is too small or too similar to the training data. Further evaluation on an unseen test set is recommended to confirm generalizability.¶

from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Flatten, Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

# Load pre-trained VGG-16
vgg_base = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(200, 200, 3))

# Freeze base layers
for layer in vgg_base.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

# Add custom classifier
x = vgg_base.output
x = Flatten()(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
output = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)

vgg_aug_model = Model(inputs=vgg_base.input, outputs=output)

Data augmentation enhanced the diversity of the training data without increasing the dataset size, helping the model become more robust to real-world variations in pose, lighting, and camera angles. This result demonstrates that combining transfer learning with augmentation is highly effective for helmet detection tasks in industrial settings.¶

Choose the Final Model¶

While all VGG-based models achieved perfect validation accuracy, the model trained with data augmentation is preferred as it introduces robustness to real-world variations like worker movement, lighting, and angles. This makes it better suited for practical deployment in diverse environments, reducing the risk of overfitting and improving generalization.
